      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">Sunday</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Sol</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Roman sun god — Sol Invictus, the unconquered sun</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        Every Sunday on the Gregorian calendar honors the sun-god of Rome. His name was <strong>Sol</strong>, and in his most powerful form he was called <strong>Sol Invictus</strong> — "the unconquered sun." For centuries before the Romans had ever heard of Yahuah, they bowed to the sun on the first day of the week.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Sol was Rome's name for the sun as a deity. The Greeks called him Helios. The Persians called him Mithras. The Egyptians called him Ra. Across the ancient world, the same star received different names but the same worship. The Romans inherited and combined these traditions, eventually elevating the sun-god to the title <em>Sol Invictus</em> — the Unconquered Sun — and making him a state deity in the third century.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Roman emperor Aurelian made Sol Invictus the chief god of the empire in AD 274 and dedicated December 25 as his birthday — the "birth of the unconquered sun" — celebrated near the winter solstice when the days began lengthening again. The day of the week dedicated to him was the first day, called <em>dies Solis</em> — the day of Sol. When the Germanic peoples adopted the Roman week, they translated the name directly: Old English <em>Sunnandæg</em>, "Sun's day," becoming Sunday.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Sun-worship is one of the oldest forms of idolatry, and Yahuah named it specifically as an abomination.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Deuteronomy 4:19</span> — "And lest thou lift up thine eyes unto heaven, and when thou seest the sun, and the moon, and the stars, even all the host of heaven, shouldest be driven to worship them, and serve them…"
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">2 Kings 23:11</span> — "And he took away the horses that the kings of Judah had given to the sun… and burned the chariots of the sun with fire."
      </div>

      <p>
        King Josiah's reform specifically targeted sun-worship that had crept into Jerusalem itself. Horses dedicated to the sun, chariots dedicated to the sun — these were not foreign practices brought in by outsiders. They were Israelite practices that had to be torn out by the roots. The temptation to honor the sun has always been close at hand for Yahuah's people, because the sun is the most visible and most powerful object in the heavens. But it was made by Yahuah on the fourth day of creation. It is a servant. It is not a god.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        The instinct of many believers, when they learn this, is to ask: <em>"Then what day in Yahuah's calendar is Sunday really?"</em> The question itself is the mistake.
      </p>

      <p>
        Sunday is a Roman day named after a Roman sun-god. It belongs to Babylon's clock — the continuous seven-day rotation tied to pagan deities. Yahuah's clock does not have a Sunday. Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He hung in the heavens. The new moon is Day 1 of the month — a non-work day, though not a Sabbath. From there the days are numbered, and the Sabbaths fall on Days 8, 15, 22, and 29. When the next new moon appears, the count resets.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>There is no Sunday in this system. There is no Monday. There is no Saturday.</strong> The Roman week and Yahuah's reckoning are two different clocks, running on different principles, and they do not translate into each other. Trying to map them is what produces confused teaching like "the church meets on the Lord's Day on Sunday" or "the Sabbath used to be Saturday and now it's Sunday." Both statements take a Roman day-name and pin a heavenly question to it. Both are mixing clocks.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Knowing where the name "Sunday" came from does not necessarily mean a believer must stop saying it — language is what it is, and most who use the word have no idea of its origin. But knowing the origin matters. It matters because the modern church has built entire doctrines on top of "Sunday" without ever asking whose name it bears. The first day of the Roman week was given to the unconquered sun — not to the Father, not to the Son, not to anything in Yahuah's order.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them what day it is. The world watches its phone and lets a sun-god tell it what day it is. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        Sunday is Sol's day. The sun in the sky is not Sol — it is the greater light Yahuah hung in the firmament on the fourth day of creation, and it has never asked for a day named after it.
      </div>

